}

{
  "analysis": "Git has been successfully installed. Now I can proceed with creating the bare git repository.",
  "plan": "I'll create a bare git repository named 'server.git' in the /git directory. This will be used for cloning and pushing.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "git init --bare server.git\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "I've successfully created a bare git repository named 'server.git'. Now I need to create a post-receive hook that will automatically deploy files to the web server directory when changes are pushed to this repository.",
  "plan": "I'll navigate to the hooks directory of the bare repository and create a post-receive hook script. This script will checkout the files to the web server directory (/var/www) whenever someone pushes to the repository.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd server.git/hooks\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cat > post-receive << 'EOF'\n#!/bin/bash\nGIT_WORK_TREE=/var/www git checkout -f\nEOF\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "I've created the post-receive hook script. Now I need to make it executable so that it can be run when changes are pushed to the repository.",
  "plan": "I'll make the post-receive hook executable using chmod, and then verify its permissions.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "chmod +x post-receive\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la post-receive\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The post-receive hook is now executable. Next, I need to set up a web server to serve the files from /var/www. I'll use Python's built-in HTTP server since it's simple to set up.",
  "plan": "I'll install Python3 if it's not already available, then create a simple script to start the web server on port 8080 serving files from /var/www.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "which python3\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "Python3 is already installed. Now I'll create a simple script to start the web server on port 8080 serving files from /var/www.",
  "plan": "I'll create a script in /usr/local/bin called 'start-webserver.sh' that will start the Python HTTP server on port 8080 with the document root at /var/www. Then I'll make it executable.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cat > /usr/local/bin/start-webserver.sh << 'EOF'\n#!/bin/bash\npython3 -m http.server 8080 --directory /var/www\nEOF\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "chmod +x /usr/local/bin/start-webserver.sh\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "I've created and made executable a script to start the web server. However, for a production environment, we'd want the web server to run in the background and restart automatically if it crashes. For simplicity in this setup, I'll just run it directly in the background. But first, let's test if our git setup works correctly.",
  "plan": "Let's create a test file in /var/www to ensure our web server will have something to serve, then start the web server in the background. After that, I'll test that everything works together.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '<html><body><h1>Default Page</h1></body></html>' > /var/www/index.html\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "nohup /usr/local/bin/start-webserver.sh > /var/log/webserver.log 2>&1 &\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "I've started the web server in the background. Let's verify that it's running and accessible.",
  "plan": "I'll check if the web server process is running and then try to access it using curl to see if it serves our default page.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ps aux | grep python3\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The web server is running (process ID 606). Now let's test if it's accessible using curl.",
